passages.text: European IG and HY TMT update

Earnings season wrapped up this week with updates from: Altice France, Altice International, Bertelsmann, eir, Iliad, Salt and TDC Net. In the news, AT&T acquired spectrum licences from Echostar in a \(\) 23bn\(transaction; Ericsson completed the sale of iconectiv. The primary market picked up, with new issuance from Orange and Telstra. Following the discussion of sector news, we continue to our usual charts and tables. Issuers highlighted: ALTICE, BERTEL, EIRCOM, ERICB, ILDFP, MATTER, ORAFP, SFRFP, T, TDCDC, TLSAU.

Altice France (SFRFP): Weak headline numbers as both fixed and mobile service revenues fell short. Group pro- forma revenues (excluding La Poste Mobile), declined \(9.1\%\) to €2,288m (JPM \(e2,347m\) ). Residential service revenues fell well short of our expectations, down \(9.1\%\) to €1,444m (JPM \(e1,499m\) ). Pro- forma EBITDA declined \(10.8\%\) to €801m (JPM \(e822m\) ), with margins down 70bp y/y. This reflects the drop- through of the greater- than- expected decline in service revenues and slowing construction. Balance sheet and cash flows: Lower capex expected to offset EBITDA drags in 2025. Altice reported accrued capex of €383m (JPM \(e433m\) ), down \(23.8\%\) y/y, with investments falling to \(16.2\%\) of sales. The company believes investment reductions are sustainable, given the reduced network investment as well as lower success- based capex in a less dynamic French market. The company reported OpFCF of €423m, up \(5.1\%\) y/y with management reiterating expectations for OpFCF growth in 2025, as lower capex offsets easing EBITDA drags (management says "EBITDA should improve but will remain in negative territory"). The company ended the period with net debt of €21.4bn (JPM \(e21.2bn\) ). The company is in the holistic financial restructuring implementation phase, with expected closing on October 1. Altice France reported pro- forma net leverage of \(5.0x\) , up from 4.8x at Q125. We maintain our Overweight recommendation on Altice France, with the restructuring a significant milestone towards potential consolidation attempts in the French market. See our recent notes (here and here), for scenario and sensitivities for creditors.

Altice International (ALTICE): Small earnings beat; IBC stake to be sold, interest in HOT Mobile confirmed (see our note here). Altice International's operational results came in slightly ahead of our expectations. Group revenues (excluding Geodesia) of €1,066m (JPM \(e1,058m\) ) rose \(1.1\%\) \((+2.3\%\) c/c); Group EBITDA of €391m (JPM \(e389m\) ) declined \(3.9\%\) \((- 2.5\%\) c/c). Accrued capex amounted to €190m this quarter (JPM \(e180m\) ), representing \(18\%\) of group revenues, driving Q1 OpFCF of €205m. Net debt ended the period at €8.7bn (JPM \(e8.7bn\) ) corresponding to total net leverage of \(5.4x\) ; 5.1x through secured. With the Q2 release, Altice confirmed that subsidiary (HOT) signed an agreement to monetise the \(23\%\) stake in Israeli FibreCo, IBC. Transaction closing is expected by YE25, with net proceeds expected to remain on balance sheet to support group liquidity. Altice said it is weighing an offer received for the Israeli mobile business (see here), although there is currently "nothing to report". Portuguese datacentres and real estate assets were flagged as potential monetisation candidates. Altice International securities trade at steep discounts ahead of meaningful 2027 maturities, and we believe caution is warranted. We note the use of asset sale proceeds in the restructuring transaction of sister company, Altice France. Creditors have begun to organise, with reports of co- op groups forming, ahead of the restructuring of sister company, Altice France (see here for details), which features common ownership and documentation, which is similar in key regards.

- AT&T (T): To acquire Spectrum licences from Ehostar for \(\sim\) 23bn. AT&T will acquire \(\sim\) 30MHz of nationwide 3.45GHz mid-band spectrum and \(\sim\) 20MHz of nationwide 600MHz low-band spectrum in an all-cash transaction. The company intends to finance the transaction with cash on hand and incremental borrowings. Following the closing (expected mid-2026), AT&T expects net leverage to increase to the 3x range (2.64x at Q225) and to return to a level consistent with its leverage target in the 2.5x range within about three years, through a combination of accelerated EBITDA growth and debt reduction resulting from strong FCF beginning in 2028. With the announcement, the company reiterated FY25 guidance and capital return plans, including \(\$ 20bn\) of capacity for share repurchases during 2025-27. AT&T also expects to maintain a consistent approach to capital returns during 2028-29, while reducing net leverage, supported by improved long-term service revenue and EBITDA growth from the transaction coupled with robust FCF. We note the company tapped the primary markets in March with a 3-part €2.75bn bond offering, issuing €1bn 3.150% due 2030, €1bn 3.60% due 2033 and €750m 4.050% due 2037, with proceeds earmarked for GCP. We reiterate our Neutral recommendation. Competitive intensity in the US market has ticked up, with AT&T doing well in broadband; however, the operator is lagging its peers slightly in mobile. Relative value is less clear, with AT&T trading at similar spreads to slightly better rated Verizon.

- Bertelsmann (BERTEL): Reported H1 numbers this week, seeing revenue growth and stable EBITDA. Revenues of €9,084m were up 1.1% y/y organically due to robust performance from RTL's streaming businesses, Arvato Group, Bertelsmann Education Group and Bertelsmann Investments. The RTL segment was down 4.4% on a challenging economic environment and lower TV advertising and Fremantle revenues, offset by streaming services (RTL+ and M6+), which grew +27% y/y. In July, the company completed the €1.1bn sale of RTL Nederland to DPG Media. Penguin Random House saw modest growth (+2.7% y/y) during the period, driven by the success of new titles and strong backlist performance. Adjusted operating EBITDA was stable y/y, with margins down 10bps y/y €13.8%. Net debt increased to €4,093m (€2,883m FY24) primarily on increased investment activities (€879m) alongside interest and dividend payments (€220m). retail broadband base increased, with net \(\mathrm{at} \mathrm{as}\) of \(+4\mathrm{k}\) (Q1: \(- 1\mathrm{k}\) ) and continued wholesale losses of \(- 11\mathrm{k}\) (Q1: \(- 10\mathrm{k}\) ). Consumer- blended fixed ARPU grew \(+0.8\%\) y/y to €49.4 (Q1: €48.2) and the group has now switched \(5\%\) of the broadband base to fibre, \(+2\%\) y/y. Mobile growth was fuelled by robust postpaid additions of \(+22\mathrm{k}\) (Q1: \(+19\mathrm{k}\) ), whilst mobile blended ARPU was down \(5\%\) y/y, with postpaid churn down sequentially to \(0.9\%\) . EBITDA of €156m (JPM: €151m) came \(3.3\%\) ahead on a decrease in pay costs. Group capex came in at €67m (JPM: €58m), down \(- 4\%\) y/y, representing capex intensity of \(21\%\) driven by the ongoing fibre rollout, mobile network upgrades and expansion programmes. Eir now has \(1.4\mathrm{m}\) in the FTTH base \((+11\%\) y/y), with \(40\%\) of passed premises connected to the fibre network. Consolidated net debt was broadly stable sequentially at €2.9bn (€2.9bn Q125). We note eir plans to refinance a portion of the outstanding \(3.5\%\) 2026 SSNs with a €300m add- on of the existing TLB5, due May 2029. This follows the recent issuance of €550m SSNs due 2031, with proceeds earmarked to i) repay €300m of the remaining May 2026 B4 senior TL; ii) part repay €152m of the May 2026 bond, leaving €400m outstanding; iii) repay €50m RCF; iv) for GCP, net of refinancing fees. Net leverage corresponded to \(4.7\mathrm{x}(4.7\mathrm{x}Q125)\) . For FY25, eir expects a low single- digit EBITDA increase, \(17 - 19\%\) capex intensity and continued strong organic cash- flow generation. We reaffirm our recently upgraded Neutral recommendation (see here) on the group. Eir has stabilised its operating performance in the three- player Irish market and is on track to deliver revenue and EBITDA growth with leading shares in Consumer, Business and Wholesale. Further, the FTTH roll- out is going to plan, with €80- 100m of cash- flow improvements from 2028 onwards. We believe spreads appear fair value, now trading wide of better rated sister company, Salt.

- Ericsson (ERICB): Completes sale of iconectiv to Koch Equity Development (see here). The company's cash benefit is expected to be \(\sim\) SEK 9.9bn ( \(\sim\) \$1bn), recording a one-off EBIT benefit of \(\sim\) SEK 7.6bn ( \(\sim\) \$0.8bn) in Q325. The company's contribution to Ericsson's 2024 net income was \(\sim\) SEK 1bn (\$0.1bn). Iconectiv serves \(>5,000\) customers across various sectors as a leading provider in number portability solutions, and a provider of core network and operations management, numbering and data exchange services. We maintain our Neutral recommendation on Ericsson. The company appears to be faring reasonably YTD, buoyed by US market share gains (partly offset by currency headwinds) and improved Licensing revenues. So far, trade pressures have been manageable, with some limited tariff impacts and noting the potential for supply chain adjustments ahead. The company recently completed a restructuring process and we believe the company maintains a solid balance sheet and liquidity. The mid-term prospects for the Equipment sector appear supportive.

- Iliad (ILDFP): Reported Q1 results with revenues behind, EBITDAaL ahead and leverage continuing to decline. Q2 revenues were up \(+1.8\%\) y/y to €2,551m (JPM: €2,593m), on \(3\%\) service revenue growth driven by growth across all markets (France: \(+1.8\%\) , Italy: \(9.1\%\) , Poland: \(4\%\) ). With Q2 results, Iliad has ceased reporting ARPUs and reduced subscriber level detail. In France, the company reported revenues of €1,640m, up \(1.8\%\) , bolstered by growth in equipment revenues \((+19.4\%)\) while service revenue growth was more muted \((+0.9\%)\) . The French market remains "fiercely" competitive as evidenced by Iliad's softening KPIs and slowing growth with fixed service revenue growth \((+2.3\%)\) offset partly by soft mobile service revenues \((- 1.1\%)\) . On the call management said ARPU remained stable q/q, suggesting softening trends y/y, while net adds across both mobile and broadband remained relatively stable. EBITDAaL grew by \(10.7\%\) to €733m on an impressive \(+360\mathrm{bp}\) margin uplift, which management attributed to operating leverage and BTS projects. In Italy, revenues grew \(9.1\%\) y/y to €306m. Service revenues grew \(9.4\%\) supported by continued volume growth, adding \(+287\mathrm{k}\) mobile and \(+32\mathrm{k}\) fibre subscribers in the period. EBITDAaL rose \(34.2\%\) to €102m, with operating leverage driving 619bps of margin improvement to \(33.3\%\) .
